<appendix id="installation">
<title>Installation</title>

<sect1 id="getting-klinpopup">
<title>How to obtain &klinpopup;</title>

<para>
KLinPopup is available at <ulink url="http://www.gerdfleischer.de/klinpopup.php">The &klinpopup; home page</ulink>
</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="requirements">
<title>Requirements</title>

<para>
In order to successfully use &klinpopup;, you need &kde;  >=3.2.
Also samba and smbclient should be installed and configured right (e.g. name resolution).
To receive message the samba server should be running.
</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="compilation">
<title>Compilation and Installation</title>

<para>
In order to compile and install KLinPopup on your system, type the following in the base directory of the KLinPopup distribution:
</para>

<screen>
% <command>./configure</command>
% <command>make</command>
% <command>make install</command>
</screen>

<para>
Since KLinPopup uses <command>autoconf</command> and <command>automake</command> you should have no trouble compiling it. Should you run into problems please mail to <email>gerdfleischer@web.de</email>.
</para>
</sect1>

<sect1 id="configuration">
<title>Configuration</title>

<para>
You must configure samba correctly.
Add or change this line in smb.conf:
<screen>
message command = sh -c '_PATH_TO_/receivepopup.sh "%f" "%m" "%I" "%s"' &#038;
</screen>
(of course the real path for _PATH_TO_, e.g. for SuSE /opt/kde3/bin, for Debian /usr/bin)
</para>

<para>
Then you should create the appropriate directory where the messages go to.
<screen>
<command>mkdir -vp -m 0777 /var/lib/klinpopup</command>
</screen>
At least make sure that samba can write in this directory.
</para>

</sect1>

</appendix>

